@NODE DecHex "Decimal and Hexdecimal Numbers"
@{b}DECIMAL AND HEXADECIMAL NUMBERS:@{ub}

All numbers, EXCEPT for percent numbers, are
hexadecimal. Hexadecimal?, you ask. Calm down, it will be explained. 
Our normal number system has the base 10; The first place has the 
value 1, the second 10, the third 100, and so on. E.g:

           236
     2*100///
     3*10_//
     6*1__/
     = dec 236

     In hexadecimal, the base is dec 16:

           3A4
     2*256///
     10*16//	<--- Those numbers showed in decimal.
     4*1__/
     = dec 676

But then there must be 16 numbers!? Right, but since we only 
have our normal 10, you use A, B, C, D, E and F as 10, 11, 12, 13, 14 
and 15. If you want to type dec (decimal, base 10) 11 in hex, it will 
be B. Simple. The reason of using this strange (?) system is that it 
takes less space; With just two digits you can write numbers up to hex FF 
(dec 255), not only up to dec 99.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Words "Strange Words"
@{b}STRANGE WORDS:@{ub}
BPM = Beats Per Minute
EMOD = Extended MODule, the preferred disk format when using QC.
LMB = Left Mouse Button
LFO = Low Frequency Oscillation
RMB = Right Mouse Button

@ENDNODE

@NODE UDGadget "Up / Down Gadget"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}UP/DOWN GADGET:@{ub}

    +--+
    | /|
    |/ |
    +--+

Pressing the @{"LMB" LINK Words} over the up/down-wards pointing triangle will
in/de-crease the value in the recessed box beside. If the @{"RMB" LINK Words} is
pressed simultaneously, the rate of change will increase.
All values are displayed in @{"hexadecimal" LINK DecHex}, except for the percentage values
(otherwise it would be a bit confusing).

@ENDNODE

@NODE CycleGadget "Cycle Gadget"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}CYCLE GADGET:@{ub}

    +---+
    |/->|
    ||  |
    |\-/|
    +---+

Cycles through multiple choices then clicked on with @{"LMB" LINK Words}. Pressing shift
while clicking will make the cycle go backwards.

@ENDNODE

@NODE LRDots "Little Red Dots"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}LITTLE RED DOTS:@{ub}
If a gadget has a little red dot in its upper right corner, then
there is an option window attached to it. Clicking @{"RMB" LINK Words} brings it up.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MenuWindow "Menu Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}MENU WINDOW:@{ub}
This is the only window that must be open all the time. From this you can
open the other windows. In this window are also the module control gadgets.

@{b}      MENU@{ub}
     +---+---+
     |@{" 1" LINK MainNoteWindow}|@{" 2" LINK SampleWindow}|
     +---+---+
     |@{" 3" LINK DiskOperationWindow}|@{" 4" LINK MixerWindow}|
     +---+---+
     |@{" 5" LINK TextWindow}|@{" 6" LINK NoteEditWindow}|
     +---+---+
     |@{" 7" LINK SpectrumAnalyzerWindow}|@{" 8" LINK QuadraScopeWindow}|
     +---+---+
     |@{" 9" LINK SplitWindow}|@{"10" LINK MIDIInWindow}|
     +---+---+
     |@{"11" LINK PreferencesWindow}|@{"12" LINK 12}|
     +---+---+
     +---+---+
     |@{"13" LINK 13}|@{"14" LINK 14}|
     +---+---+
     |@{"15" LINK 15}|@{"16" LINK 16}|
     +---+---+
     |@{"17" LINK 17}|@{"18" LINK 18}|
     +---+---+


  1) Opens the @{"main note window" LINK MainNoteWindow}.
  2) Opens the @{"sample window" LINK SampleWindow}.
  3) Opens the @{"disk operation window" LINK DiskOperationWindow}.
  4) Opens the @{"mixer window" LINK MixerWindow}.
  5) Opens the @{"text display window" LINK TextWindow}.
  6) Opens the @{"note edit window" LINK NoteEditWindow}.
  7) Opens the @{"spectrum analyzer window" LINK SpectrumAnalyzerWindow}.
  8) Opens the @{"scope window" LINK QuadrascopeWindow}.
  9) Opens the @{"split keyboard window" LINK SplitWindow}.
 10) Opens the @{"MIDI in window" LINK MIDIInWindow}.
 11) Opens the @{"preferences window" LINK PreferencesWindow}.
 12) Displays the About requester.

 13) Plays the module from the current position.
 14) Plays the current pattern.
 15) Starts recording.
 16) Starts recording the current pattern.
 17) Stops the music, turns the sound off and turns edit off.
 18) Turns edit on.

When you press the CLOSE gadget in the upper left corner, the whole program
will be ended.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MainNoteWindow "Main Note Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}MAIN NOTE WINDOW:@{ub}
This is the main window of Quadra Composer. It displays the current
pattern, and it contains most gadgets for note editing.

      @{b}MAIN NOTE WINDOW@{ub}
     +------------------------------------------------+
     |@{"          On      On   1    On       On        " LINK mnw_DragBar}|
     +-----+------------------------------------+-----+
     | @{"01" LINK mnw_Position} |                                    | @{"01" LINK mnw_EditSkip} |
     | @{"23" LINK mnw_Pattern} |                                    | @{"01" LINK mnw_Quantisizing} |
     | @{"23" LINK mnw_CurrentPattern} |                                    | @{"On" LINK mnw_Multi} |
     | @{"3F" LINK mnw_PatternLength} |                                    | @{"02" LINK mnw_Multi14} |
     | @{"05" LINK mnw_SampleNumber} |                                    | @{"03" LINK mnw_Multi14} |
     | @{"7D" LINK mnw_Tempo} |         @{"Pattern Display" LINK mnw_PatternDisplay}           | @{"04" LINK mnw_Multi14} |
     | @{"CI" LINK mnw_Timing} |                                    | @{"01" LINK mnw_Multi14} |
     | @{"02" LINK mnw_SongLength} |                                    | @{"Of" LINK mnw_AutoEcho} |
     |     |                                    | @{"02" LINK mnw_AutoEchoSpace} |
     |@{"C" LINK mnw_Cut}@{"C" LINK mnw_Copy} |                                    | @{"50" LINK mnw_AutoEchoCut} |
     |@{"P" LINK mnw_Paste}@{"C" LINK mnw_Clear} |                                    | @{"Of" LINK mnw_Split} |
     +-----+------------------------------------+-----+
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_DragBar "Dragbar"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}DRAGBAR@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
This one displays four On/Off's, which informs you about the voice status.
You can toggle a voice by clicking on it using @{"RMB" LINK Words}. If
a voice is set to off, no sound will be heared from it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_PatternDisplay "PatternDisplay"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}PATTERN DISPLAY@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
This is the place where you edit the patterns, by using the keyboard. To edit
the notes you must be in edit mode (press [space]). When you go into edit mode 
the cursor turns red (unshaded). To move around in the pattern, use the 
arrowkeys (NOT on the numeric keyboard). You can mark notes by using the 
mouse, or the keyboard (press Amiga-M).
The pattern grafix routine is changed a bit in v2.1. It is now totally
dynamic, thus saving the 80kb cache which it used to allocate before.
Due to this, it might be a bit slower than before, but I hope you don't
mind.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Position "Position"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}POS. (POSITION)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
Use this to cycle trough the @{"positions" LINK PatternsPositions} (@{"hex" LINK DecHex} 00-FF).
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Pattern "Pattern"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}PATT. (PATTERN)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}

This is the pattern attached to the current position. You can change this to 
"mix" the patterns together to a song. But, it's better to use the mixer 
(see @{"Mixer Window" LINK MixerWindow}) instead to put your song together.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_CurrentPattern "Current Pattern"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}C. PATT (CURRENT PATTERN)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}

This gadget is used to change the current displayed pattern, i.e NOT the 
pattern attached to a position.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_PatternLength "Pattern Length"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}PATTL. (PATTERN LENGTH)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}

Use this gadget to change the length of the current pattern. The length may 
vary from 1 to 256 lines, but the value displayed is the number of the last 
line (number of lines - 1).
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_SampleNumber "Sample Number"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}SAMPLE NUMBER@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}

This gadget is actually duplicated, it can also be found in the
@{"sample window" LINK SampleWindow} Use this gadget to change the current sample number. You
can use up to 255 samples (number zero cannot be used).
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Tempo "Tempo"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}TEMPO@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
This gadget sets the @{"BPM" LINK Words} rate. The tempo may vary from 32 to 255 (@{"hex" LINK DecHex}20 to FF)
@{"BPM" LINK Words}. Normally this rate is set to 125 (@{"hex" LINK DecHex} 7D).
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Timing "Timing"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}TIMING@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
Toggles between CIA (CI) and vertical blank (VB) timing. Normally you should
use the CIA timing, because you can only change tempo in this mode. The 
vertical blank timing is mostly used by demo coders, who don't want to waste 
the level 6 or 2 irq on music. If you use the vertical blank timing in the 
speed will vary depending on the screen mode.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_SongLength "Song Length"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}SONGL. (SONG LENGTH)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
Decides how many positions will be used.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Cut "Cut"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}CUT@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
Copies the @{"marked" LINK mnw_PatternDisplay} note block to the note copy
buffer, and moves the rest of the pattern up.
This function can be started by pressing "F3" too.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Copy "Copy"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}COPY@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
Copies the @{"marked" LINK mnw_PatternDisplay} note block to the note copy buffer.
This function can be started by pressing "F4" too.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Paste "Paste"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}PASTE@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
Inserts the note copy buffer at the sample cursor. This can be achieved by
pressing "F5", too.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Clear "Clear"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}CLEAR@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
Removes the @{"marked" LINK mnw_PatternDisplay} note block and moves the
rest of the pattern up.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_EditSkip "Edit Skip"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}E. SKIP (EDIT SKIP)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
Sets the number of rows to jump down after typing a note. Default is 01.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Quantisizing "Quantisizing"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}QUANT. (QUANTISIZING)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
Quantisizing lets you set if the notes you type should be on every two rows, 
every three rows, and so on. Very useful if you're recording e.g a drumbeat
in realtime.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Multi "Multi"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}MULTI (MULTI KEYBOARD)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
If you turn this on, the cursor will skip to another track after typing
a note.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Multi14 "Multi 1 - 4"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}MULTI 1 - 4@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
Multi 1 sets where the cursor will skip after typing a note in track 1,
and so on.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_AutoEcho "Auto Echo"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}A. ECHO (AUTO ECHO)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}
This sets whether the funny little effect called Auto Echo will be on or
off. Auto Echo makes a kind of echo after each note typed, based on the 
default volume of the sample. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_AutoEchoSpace "Auto Echo Space"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}AE.SPC (Auto Echo Space)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}

Sets the space between the auto echoes.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_AutoEchoCut "Auto Echo Cut %"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}AE. CUT% (AUTO ECHO CUT %)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}

This is the percentage of volume cut off the volume for each echo. When 
the volume reaches 4 or lower, the echo stops.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mnw_Split "Keyboard Split"
@TOC MainNoteWindow
@{b}SPLIT (KEYBOARD SPLIT)@{ub} @{i}(Main Note Window)@{ui}

This is where you tell Quadra Composer to use a keyboard split, and which
one. A keyboard split lets you use more than one sample on the keyboard.
This is useful for i.e drums, or multisampled sounds.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SampleWindow "Sample Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}SAMPLE WINDOW:@{ub}
Well, this is actually the biggest part of Quadra Composer (in bytes), so
we hope that it will be useful. You don't actually have to use Quadra
Composer as a music program, you can use it only as a sample edit program.
The sample editor supports 16 bit editing, but you can still not load and
save 16 bit sounds (sorry :-(). If you own a sample synth, and would like to 
use Quadra Composer to edit the samples, please send us a reference for the
sample and disk format, and we'll try to implement some 16 bit load and
save functions.

      @{b}SAMPLE@{ub}
     +-------------------------------------+
     |                                     |
     |                                     |
     |            @{"Sample Display" LINK sw_SampleDisplay}          |
     |                                     |
     |                                     |
     |                                     |
     +-------------------------------------+
     | @{"C4" LINK sw_Period}  @{"01A44  " LINK sw_Length}  @{"01" LINK sw_SampleNumber}       @{"  < " LINK sw_SampleLeft}@{" >  " LINK sw_SampleRight} |
     | @{"40" LINK sw_Volume}  Play...  @{"Range All" LINK sw_RangeAll} @{"Backw.   " LINK sw_BackWards} |
     | @{"+1" LINK sw_FineTune}  @{"All    " LINK sw_PlayAll} @{"Zoom Out " LINK sw_ZoomOut} @{"Inverse  " LINK sw_Inverse} |
     | @{"On" LINK sw_Loop}  @{"Display" LINK sw_PlayDisplay} Smp.+Info  @{"Center   " LINK sw_Center} |
     |      @{"Range  " LINK sw_PlayRange} @{"Copy...  " LINK sw_CopySampleInfo} @{"Tone     " LINK sw_Tone} |
     |      Show...  @{"Clear... " LINK sw_ClearSampleInfo} @{"Sample..." LINK sw_Sample} |
     | @{"C" LINK sw_Cut}@{"C" LINK sw_Copy} @{"All    " LINK sw_ShowAll}            @{"Edit...  " LINK SampleEditWindow} |
     | @{"P" LINK sw_Paste}@{"C" LINK sw_Clear} @{"Range  " LINK sw_ShowRange}                       |
     +-------------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_SampleDisplay "Sample Display"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}SAMPLE DISPLAY @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

This is where the current sample, or a part of it, is shown. You can 
mark the sample or a part of it by using your mouse. If you want to 
extend or shorten the range, just press shift when clicking, and 
the nearest border will be changed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_SampleDisplay "Sample Display"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}SAMPLE DISPLAY @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Period "Period"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}PERIOD @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the standard period, used by the "Play"
gadgets, and some effects like "Tune", "Resample" or "Pitch".
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Volume "Volume"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}VOLUME @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the default volume of the current sample.
When playing the sample (without setting a new volume) this volume
will be used as default.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Finetune "Finetune"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}F.TUNE (FINETUNE) @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the finetune value of the current sample. Finetune is
used to make "untuned" samples sound a bit better. Every finetune step
corresponds to about 1/16 of a halftone.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Loop "Loop"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}LOOP @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

You can turn the loop on or off by using this gadget (surprise!).
When the loop is on, the loop "pointers" will be shown in the 
@{"Sample Display" LINK sw_SampleDisplay}. You can change the loop by
clicking in the upper square of the loop "pointers".
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Cut "Cut"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}CUT @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Cuts the range to the sample copy buffer. This can also be achieved 
by pressing "F3".
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Copy "Copy"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}COPY @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Copies the range to the sample copy buffer. This can aslo be achieved
by pressing "F4" 
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Paste "Paste"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}PASTE @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Inserts the sample copy buffer in the current sample, starting at
the sample cursor if it exists, otherwise in the current range.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Clear "Clear"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}CLEAR @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Removes the marked range from the sample. This will @{b}NOT@{ub} affect the
copy buffer.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Length "Length"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}SAMPLE LENGTH @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Here you can extend / shorten the current sample. If a sample is shortened
more than 2 bytes, a "Are you sure?" requester will appear. This is because
the sample will be cut after the endpoint, and all information will be
lost...
If you want to extend / shorten the sample much, just keep the button
pressed, 'cause the speed will be accelerated.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_PlayAll "Play All"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}PLAY ALL @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Plays the whole sample (and the loop), using the standard pitch.
@{i}Note@{ui}: If you're in edit mode, the computer multitasking will be turned
off as the sound is played...
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_PlayDisplay "Play Display"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}PLAY DISPLAY @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Plays the the visible part of sample (excl. the loop), using the standard 
pitch. 
@{i}Note:@{ui} If you're in edit mode, the computer multitasking will
be turned off as the sound is played...
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_PlayRange "Play Range"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}PLAY RANGE @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Plays the range (if present), using the standard pitch.
@{i}Note:@{ui} If you're in edit mode, the computer multitasking will be turned
off as the sound is played...
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_ShowAll "Show All"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}SHOW ALL @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Shows the whole sample (zooms out to the max.).
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_ShowRange "Show Range"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}SHOW RANGE @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Shows the range of the sample (most often means zooming in).
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_SampleNumber "Sample Number"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}SAMPLE NUMBER @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

This is where yu determine which sample to work with. This gadget can
also be found in the @{"Main Note Window" LINK MainNoteWindow}
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_RangeAll "Range All"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}RANGE ALL @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Marks a range with exactly the same proportions as the whole sample
(surprise!).
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_ZoomOut "Zoom Out"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}ZOOM OUT @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Shows a bit more of the sample...
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_CopySampleInfo "Copy Sample + Info"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}COPY SAMPLE + INFO @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Displays a very tiny window where you can set the destination sample
number. Pressing copy will copy the current sample to the destination
including all info such as volume, name, loop etc. (and not only the sound
data).
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_ClearSampleInfo "Clear Sample + Info"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}CLEAR SAMPLE + INFO @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Clears the current sample data, name, volume and so on...
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_SampleLeft "Sample Left"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}SAMPLE LEFT @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Moves the sample display left (i.e moves the sample to the right (hmm?!))...
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_SampleRight "Sample Right"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}SAMPLE RIGHT @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

See @{"Sample Left" LINK sw_SampleLeft} and put NOT! in the end.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Backwards "Backwards"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}BACKW. (BACKWARDS) @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Will reverse the sample or the range.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Inverse "Inverse"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}INVERSE @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

This function will turn the sample upside down.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Center "Center"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}CENTER @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

This function will try to center the sample or the range.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Tone "Tone"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}TONE @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}

Pressing this gadget will play a boring tone, which is very useful when
tuning your samples.
A option window is attached to the button. In this the period and voice of
the tone can be set.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sw_Sample "Sample"
@TOC SampleWindow
@{b}SAMPLE @{ub}@{i}(Sample Window)@{ui}
  
When pressing this gadget the computer will be frozen, a window opened, 
and the sampler data will be heard in your speakers. In the window the 
data will be displayed, so that you can adjust the input volume. If you 
press @{"RMB" LINK Words}, the sample operation will be canceled. 
Otherwise the program will start sampling as you press @{"LMB" LINK Words}, 
and continue until you press @{"LMB" LINK Words} again, or until the sample
is 128 kB (@{"hex" LINK DecHex} 1FFFE bytes) long. 
In the option window you can turn Autostart on / off, set Autostart Sensibility, 
and turn Oversample on / off. Autostart will cause the sampling operation 
to start immediately when a sound is heard (loud enough). Oversample samples
faster than the actual sample period, to get rid of noise from the sampler.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SampleEditWindow "Sample Edit Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}SAMPLE EDIT WINDOW:@{ub}
This is the window which contains all the fun parts of sample editing,
the effects...
When opening the window the current sample will be converted to 16 bit, to retain
sound quality.
All disk operation is disabled. If you want to listen to the sample the 
processor will be used to play it (since the Amiga can only play 8 bit samples), 
which will cause the computer to freeze until you either press a mousebutton, 
or 'til the whole sound is played. 

      @{b}SAMPLE EDIT WINDOW@{ub}
     +----------+----------+
     |@{"Tune     " LINK sew_Tune} @{"Chord... " LINK sew_Chord}|
     |@{"Volume..." LINK sew_Volume} @{"Synth... " LINK sew_Synth}|
     |@{"Mix...   " LINK sew_Mix} @{"Pitch    " LINK sew_Pitch}|
     |@{"Oct. Up  " LINK sew_OctaveUp} Filters:  |
     |@{"Oct. Down" LINK sew_OctaveDown} @{"Analyze.." LINK sew_Analyze}|
     |@{"Echo...  " LINK sew_Echo} @{"Delta... " LINK sew_Delta}|
     |@{"Flange..." LINK sew_Flange} @{"Boost1   " LINK sew_Boost1}|
     |@{"Resample " LINK sew_Resample} @{"Boost2   " LINK sew_Boost2}|
     |                     |
     |@{"OK       " LINK sew_OK} @{"Cancel   " LINK sew_Cancel}|
     +----------+----------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Tune "Tune"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}TUNE@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Tune "Tune"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}TUNE@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

Use this function to tune samples so that they fit sound good together. 
First, turn on the 'Tunetone'. Second, find the matching period and 
finetune (by listening), and set the values in the Period and F.Tune gadgets. 
Third, if you want, you can set the desired Tune To period in the Tuning 
Options window. Fourth, press the 'Tune' button.
@ENDNODE
 
@NODE sew_Volume "Volume"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}VOLUME@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

This function is used to change the volume of the sample. 
In the window which appears, you can find the following gadgets:

      @{b}VOLUME@{ub}
     +--------------------+
     |Startvolume %       |
     |         @{"100" LINK vow_Vol}       |
     |Endvolume %         |
     |               @{"187" LINK vow_Vol} |
     |                    |
     |@{"Maximum" LINK vow_Presets}@{"Norm" LINK vow_Presets}@{"Out" LINK vow_Presets}@{"In" LINK vow_Presets}|
     |@{"Operate" LINK vow_Operate}  @{"Op & Exit" LINK vow_Operate}|
     +--------------------+
@ENDNODE

@NODE vow_Vol "Start / End Volume %"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}START / END VOLUME %@{ub} @{i}(Volume Option Window)@{ui}

The Startvolume is the amplification value used in the beginning of the
range, and it will slide over to Endvolume. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE vow_Presets "Presets"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}PRESETS@{ub} @{i}(Volume Option Window)@{ui}

Maximum is a function which scans the sample to find out how much the 
volume can be raised without cutoff. Norm sets the sliders to 100%. 
Out sets the Startvolume to 100%, and the Endvolume to 0%, to create a 
fade out. Guess what In is...
@ENDNODE

@NODE vow_Operate "Operate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OPERATE (& EXIT)@{ub} @{i}(Volume Option Window)@{ui}

This will apply the current settings on the sample.
@{i}Note:@{ui} If range is present, the volumechange will only affect it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Mix "Mix"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}MIX@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

This function will mix the current sample with the copy buffer 
(it doesn't matter if the copy buffer is 16 or 8 bit).

      @{b}MIX@{ub}
     +--------------------+
     |Startmix %          |
     |         @{"050" LINK mow_Mix}       |
     |Endmix %            |
     |          @{"055" LINK mow_Mix}      |
     |HalfVol:            |
     | @{"On" LINK mow_HalfVol}    @{"Norm" LINK mow_Presets}@{"Out" LINK mow_Presets}@{"In" LINK mow_Presets}|
     |@{"Operate" LINK mow_Operate}  @{"Op & Exit" LINK mow_Operate}|
     +--------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE mow_Mix "Mix"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}START / END MIX@{ub} @{i}(Mix Option Window)@{ui}

The Startmix sets how much the mixed sample will be affected by the sample
and how much it will be affected by the copy buffer. E.g: If Startmix
is set to 75%, the current sample will have 75% of the volume, and the 
copy buffer 25%. Just like the Startvolume the Startmix will slide over 
to the Endmix.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mow_HalfVol "Half Volume"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}HALF VOLUME@{ub} @{i}(Mix Option Window)@{ui}

If this is on, the maximum mix settings will be 100%, otherwise 200%.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mow_Presets "Presets"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}PRESETS@{ub} @{i}(Mix Option Window)@{ui}

These presets will set the sliders to 50 / 50, 100 / 0 and 0 / 100. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE mow_Operate "Operate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OPERATE (& EXIT)@{ub} @{i}(Mix Option Window)@{ui}

This will apply the current settings on the sample.
@{i}Note:@{ui} If range is present, the mix will only affect it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_OctaveUp "Octave Up"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OCT. UP (OCTAVE UP)@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

Doubles the sample frequency (and cuts the length in two).
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_OctaveDown "Octave Down"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OCT. DOWN (OCTAVE DOWN)@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

Halves the sample frequency (and doubles the sample length).
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Echo "Echo"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}ECHO@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

Creates an echo in the sample.

      @{b}ECHO@{ub}
     +--------------------+
     |Echo Rate:          |
     |   @{"012" LINK eow_EchoDecay}             |
     |Decay Rate:         |
     |          @{"055" LINK eow_EchoDecay}      |
     |Re-Echo:            |
     | @{"On" LINK eow_ReEcho}    @{"Echo" LINK eow_Presets}@{"Reverb" LINK eow_Presets}|
     |@{"Operate" LINK eow_Operate}  @{"Op & Exit" LINK eow_Operate}|
     +--------------------+
@ENDNODE

@NODE eow_EchoDecay "Echo / Decay Rate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}ECHO / DECAY RATE@{ub} @{i}(Echo Option Window)@{ui}

Echo rate decides how fast the echo will return. Decay rate decides how fast
the echo will vanish. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE eow_ReEcho "ReEcho"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}REECHO@{ub} @{i}(Echo Option Window)@{ui}

If you turn on Re-Echo, each echo will return more often.
@ENDNODE

@NODE eow_Presets "Presets"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}PRESETS@{ub} @{i}(Echo Option Window)@{ui}

Echo and Reverb are presets, just like In and Out in the volume window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE eow_Operate "Operate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OPERATE@{ub} @{i}(Echo Option Window)@{ui}

This will apply the current settings on the sample.
@{i}Note:@{ui} If present, the range will be used as echo.
      If you set the sample cursor while the echo window is open, the Echo
      Rate will be adjusted so that the first echo will be on the sample cursor
      position.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Flange "Flange"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}FLANGE@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

Creates a "swirling" effect in the sample.

      @{b}FLANGE@{ub}
     +----------------------------+
     |Freuency: Amplitude: W.Form:|
     |   @{"011" LINK fow_Freq}      @{"020" LINK fow_Amp}      @{"/\/" LINK fow_WForm} |
     |@{"Operate" LINK fow_Operate}          @{"Op & Exit" LINK fow_Operate}|
     +----------------------------+
@ENDNODE

@NODE fow_Freq "Frequency"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}FREQUENCY@{ub} @{i}(Flange Option Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the speed of the flange. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE fow_Amp "Amplitude"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}AMPLITUDE@{ub} @{i}(Flange Option Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the amount of phasing in the flange. If you set this value
higher, it doesn't necessarily mean that you hear the effect better. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE fow_WForm "Waveform"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}WAVEFORM@{ub} @{i}(Flange Option Window)@{ui}

Here you set which waveform will be used in the phase shifting.
@ENDNODE

@NODE fow_Operate "Operate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OPERATE (& EXIT)@{ub} @{i}(Flange Option Window)@{ui}

This will apply the current settings on the sample.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_OK "OK"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OK@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

Converts the 16 bit edit buffer to 8 bit, and replaces the old 8 bit sample.
Then it closes the edit windows.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Chord "Chord"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}CHORD@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

Creates an chord by tuning and mixing the current sample.

      @{b}CHORD@{ub}
     +-------------------------------+
     |Note 1: Note 2: Note 3: Note 4:|
     |  @{"C-3" LINK cow_Note}    @{"E-3" LINK cow_Note}    @{"G-3" LINK cow_Note}    @{"Off" LINK cow_Note} |
     |@{"Major    " LINK cow_Presets}@{"Major 7   " LINK cow_Presets}@{"Sus2     " LINK cow_Presets}|
     |@{"Minor    " LINK cow_Presets}@{"Minor 7   " LINK cow_Presets}@{"Sus4     " LINK cow_Presets}|
     |@{"Operate" LINK cow_Operate}             @{"Op & Exit" LINK cow_Operate}|
     +-------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE cow_Note "Note 1 - 4"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}NOTE 1 - 4@{ub} @{i}(Chord Option Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the notes to be included in the chord. If you don't
want all the four notes to be included, just set the last to Off (below C-1).
@ENDNODE

@NODE cow_Presets "Presets"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}PRESETS@{ub} @{i}(Chord Option Window)@{ui}

Major, Minor, Major 7, Sus2, Sus4 and Minor 7 are presets, which builds a chord
based on the first note.
@ENDNODE

@NODE cow_Operate "Operate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OPERATE (& EXIT)@{ub} @{i}(Chord Option Window)@{ui}

This will apply the current settings on the sample.
@{i}Note:@{ui} The length of the sample will be adjusted to the length of the
      longest sample in the chord.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Resample "Resample"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}RESAMPLE@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

This is a very useful function: It can rebuild a sample digitally from the 
current pattern. I.e: If you have made a really groovy drum beat on tree
tracks and you don't want to waste them all in the module, just use this
function to create a sample of the drum beat digitally and thus without
quality loss...

How to use: Put the sample cursor on the first line in the pattern you
want to resample. Choose the sample frequency you want to use in the period
gadget, and press resample. The sample will now appear in the display, but
the volume will probably be rather low. Use the @{"volume change" LINK sew_Volume} function
to maximize the volume. This can of course be done without quality loss due
to the 16 bit editing. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Synth "Synth"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}Synth@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

This is a rather BIG function, which makes sounds by adding sinewaves
(additive synthesizer). In the window which appears you can find the
following gadgets:

      @{b}Synth@{ub}
     +-------------------------------+
     |Envelopes:                     |
     |@{"Cut Off..." LINK sow_CutOff}@{"Volume..." LINK sow_Volume}@{"Pitch... " LINK sow_Pitch}|
     |@{"Resonance..." LINK sow_Resonance}@{"Phase..." LINK sow_Phase}@{"Noise..." LINK sow_Noise}|
     |@{"Load...        " LINK sow_Load}@{"Save...       " LINK sow_Save}|
     |@{"Operate" LINK sow_Operate}             @{"Op & Exit" LINK sow_Operate}|
     +-------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE sow_CutOff "Cut Off"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}CUT OFF@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option Window)@{ui}

      @{b}CUT OFF@{ub}
     +-------------------------------------+
     |Number of sinewaves:                 |
     |+--------------------------------+ @{"/" LINK sowco_DrawLine}|
     ||                                |   |
     ||                                | @{"&" LINK sowco_DrawFree}|
     ||            @{"Envelope" LINK sowco_Envelope}           |   |
     ||                                |   |
     ||                                |   |
     |+--------------------------------+   |
     |LFO Frequency: LFO Amplitude: W.Form:|
     |   @{"010" LINK sowco_LFOFreq}           @{"010" LINK sowco_LFOAmp}         @{"/\/" LINK sowco_LFOWForm}  |
     +-------------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE sowco_Envelope "Envelope"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}ENVELOPE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Cut Off Window)@{ui}

This is where you draw a freehand filter curve. A flat line in the bottom
means a single sine wave, and a line at the top of the display means
a sharp sawtooth wave.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowco_DrawLine "Draw Line"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW LINE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Cut Off Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the line tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowco_DrawFree "Draw Freehand"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW FREEHAND@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Cut Off Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the freehand tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowco_LFOFreq "LFO Frequency"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LFO FREQUENCY@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Cut Off Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the frequency of the @{"LFO" LINK Words}, which modulates
the cut off envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowco_LFOAmp "LFO Amplitude"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LFO AMPLITUDE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Cut Off Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the amplitude of the @{"LFO" LINK Words}, which modulates
the cut off envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowco_LFOWForm "LFO Waveform"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LFO WAVEFORM@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Cut Off Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the waveform of the @{"LFO" LINK Words}, which modulates
the cut off envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sow_Volume "Volume"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}VOLUME@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option Window)@{ui}

      @{b}VOLUME@{ub}
     +-----------------------------------------+
     |200%+--------------------------------+ @{"/" LINK sowvo_DrawLine}|
     |    |                                |   |
     |    |                                | @{"&" LINK sowvo_DrawFree}|
     |100%|            @{"Envelope" LINK sowvo_Envelope}           |   |
     |    |                                |   |
     |    |                                |   |
     |  0%+--------------------------------+   |
     |    LFO Frequency: LFO Amplitude: W.Form:|
     |       @{"010" LINK sowvo_LFOFreq}           @{"010" LINK sowvo_LFOAmp}         @{"/\/" LINK sowvo_LFOWForm}  |
     +-----------------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE sowvo_Envelope "Envelope"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}ENVELOPE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Volume Window)@{ui}

This is where you draw a volume filter curve.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowvo_DrawLine "Draw Line"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW LINE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Volume Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the line tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowvo_DrawFree "Draw Freehand"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW FREEHAND@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Volume Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the freehand tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowvo_LFOFreq "LFO Frequency"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LFO FREQUENCY@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Volume Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the frequency of the @{"LFO" LINK Words}, which modulates
the volume envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowvo_LFOAmp "LFO Amplitude"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LFO AMPLITUDE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Volume Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the amplitude of the @{"LFO" LINK Words}, which modulates
the volume envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowvo_LFOWForm "LFO Waveform"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LFO WAVEFORM@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Volume Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the waveform of the @{"LFO" LINK Words}, which modulates
the volume envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sow_Pitch "Pitch"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}PITCH@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option Window)@{ui}

      @{b}PITCH@{ub}
     +-------------------------------------+
     |Pitch (One Octave Per Line):         |
     |+--------------------------------+ @{"/" LINK sowpi_DrawLine}|
     ||                                |   |
     ||                                | @{"&" LINK sowpi_DrawFree}|
     ||            @{"Envelope" LINK sowpi_Envelope}           |   |
     ||                                |   |
     ||                                |   |
     |+--------------------------------+   |
     |LFO Frequency: LFO Amplitude: W.Form:|
     |   @{"010" LINK sowpi_LFOFreq}           @{"010" LINK sowpi_LFOAmp}         @{"/\/" LINK sowpi_LFOWForm}  |
     +-------------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE sowpi_Envelope "Envelope"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}ENVELOPE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Pitch Window)@{ui}

This is where you draw a freehand pitch curve.
A line far down in the display means a very low tone. The red lines
point out where "C" is.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowpi_DrawLine "Draw Line"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW LINE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Pitch Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the line tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowpi_DrawFree "Draw Freehand"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW FREEHAND@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Pitch Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the freehand tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowpi_LFOFreq "LFO Frequency"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LFO FREQUENCY@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Pitch Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the frequency of the @{"LFO" LINK Words}, which modulates
the pitch envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowpi_LFOAmp "LFO Amplitude"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LFO AMPLITUDE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Pitch Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the amplitude of the @{"LFO" LINK Words}, which modulates
the pitch envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowpi_LFOWForm "LFO Waveform"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LFO WAVEFORM@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Pitch Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the waveform of the @{"LFO" LINK Words}, which modulates
the pitch envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sow_Noise "Noise"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}NOISE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option Window)@{ui}

      @{b}NOISE@{ub}
     +-----------------------------------------+
     |100%+--------------------------------+ @{"/" LINK sowno_DrawLine}|
     |    |                                |   |
     |    |                                | @{"&" LINK sowno_DrawFree}|
     |    |            @{"Envelope" LINK sowno_Envelope}           |   |
     |    |                                |   |
     |    |                                |   |
     |    +--------------------------------+   |
     +-----------------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE sowno_Envelope "Envelope"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}ENVELOPE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Noise Window)@{ui}

This is where you draw a freehand noise curve, which is only useful
when making drums (I guess).
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowno_DrawLine "Draw Line"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW LINE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Noise Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the line tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowno_DrawFree "Draw Freehand"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW FREEHAND@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Noise Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the freehand tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sow_Resonance "Resonance"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}RESONANCE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option Window)@{ui}

      @{b}RESONANCE@{ub}
     +----------------+
     |+-----------+ @{"/" LINK sowre_DrawLine}|
     ||           |   |
     ||           | @{"&" LINK sowre_DrawFree}|
     ||           |   |
     || @{"Envelope" LINK sowre_Envelope} |   |
     ||           |   |
     ||           |   |
     ||           |   |
     |+-----------+   |
     +----------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE sowre_DrawLine "Draw Line"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW LINE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Resonance Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the line tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowre_DrawFree "Draw Freehand"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW FREEHAND@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Resonance Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the freehand tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowre_Envelope "Envelope"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}ENVELOPE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Resonance Window)@{ui}

This window represents the relative volumes of the frequencies.
From the @{i}right@{ui}, the first pixel shows the volume of the
last sine wave (determined in the @{"Cut Off" LINK sow_CutOff} window), and
so on...
The resonance effect is created by pulling the low frequencies low,
like this:


     +-----------+
     |          ||
     |         / |
     |       _/  |
     |    __/    |
     |___/       |
     +-----------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE sow_Phase "Phase"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}PHASE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option Window)@{ui}

      @{b}PHASE@{ub}
     +----------------+
     |+-----------+ @{"/" LINK sowph_DrawLine}|
     ||           |   |
     ||           | @{"&" LINK sowph_DrawFree}|
     ||           |   |
     || @{"Envelope" LINK sowph_Envelope} |   |
     ||           |   |
     ||           |   |
     ||           |   |
     |+-----------+   |
     +----------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE sowph_DrawLine "Draw Line"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW LINE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Phase Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the line tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowph_DrawFree "Draw Freehand"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW FREEHAND@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Phase Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the freehand tool is used when drawing the envelope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sowph_Envelope "Envelope"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}ENVELOPE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option -> Phase Window)@{ui}

This is where you draw a freehand phase distortion curve. The curve is
a kind of translation table for angles. E.g if it is a normal corner to 
corner straight line, 10° will be 10° when the sound is made. If you draw
the line from the left-bottom corner to the middle of the right edge, 10°
will actually be 5°.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sow_Load "Load"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LOAD@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option Window)@{ui}

Asks for an IFF ENVL (Envelopes) file to load. This file contains all
of the data above.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sow_Save "Save"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}SAVE@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option Window)@{ui}

Saves your current envelopes etc. as an IFF ENVL file.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sow_Operate "Operate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OPERATE (& EXIT)@{ub} @{i}(Synth Option Window)@{ui}

When pressing this gadget, a sound with the length of the current sample
will be made. The length must be at least 256 (@{"hex" LINK DecHex} 100) bytes
long. If you want to change the length of the sample, use the @{"length" LINK sw_Length}
gadget.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Pitch "Pitch"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}PITCH@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

This funcion doesn't work as good as I want it to, but it's funny to
use on your voice to make you sound like someone else...
How to use: Set the desired period in the @{"period" LINK sw_Period} gadget, and
press "Pitch". The pitch of the sound will now be changed, without altering
length of the sound.

The option window attached to this function contains a pitch gadget, where
you can set the pitch you use on the current sound.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Analyze "Pitch"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}ANALYZE@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

This function will FFT (Fast Fourier Transform) analyze the sample, i.e
split the sound in sinewaves of drifferent phase, amplitude and frequency.
When this is done, is is very simple to cut the frequencies you don't want,
or to amplify them. When you try to play the sample, the analyzed data
will first be converted to a sample (if the data has been changed).

      @{b}ANALYZE@{ub}
     +---------------+
     | Filter:       |
     | @{"Scale..     " LINK aow_Scale} |
     | @{"Curve...    " LINK aow_FreeHand} |
     | @{"Rem Noise..." LINK aow_RemNoise} |
     |               |
     |@{"Display...    " LINK aow_Display}|
     |@{"ReAnalyze...  " LINK aow_ReAnalyze}|
     |@{"Make Sound    " LINK aow_MakeSound}|
     +---------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE aow_Scale "Scale"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}SCALE@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option Window)@{ui}

This is a function to amplify the selected range in the analyzed data.
But actually, it's mostly used to cut certain sounds from a complex sound
(set the Scale Amplitude% to 0).

      @{b}ANALYZE@{ub}
     +------------------+
     |Scale Amplitude%  |
     |@{"000" LINK aowsc_Scale}              |
     |@{"Operate" LINK aowsc_Operate}@{"Op & Exit" LINK aowsc_Operate}|
     +------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE aowsc_Scale "Scale"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}SCALE@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Scale Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the amplification factor.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowsc_Operate "Operate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OPERATE (& EXIT)@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Scale Window)@{ui}

Scales the current range in the analyzed data, but the sample will
@{b}not@{ub} be recalculated.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aow_FreeHand "Cruve"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}CURVE@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option Window)@{ui}

Using this function you can easily draw a freehand filter curve.

      @{b}CURVE@{ub}
     +-----------------------------------------+
     |200%+--------------------------------+ @{"/" LINK aowcu_DrawLine}|
     |    |                                |   |
     |    |                                | @{"&" LINK aowcu_DrawFree}|
     |100%|          @{"Filter Curve" LINK aowcu_Curve}         |   |
     |    |                                |   |
     |    |                                |   |
     |    +--------------------------------+   |
     |@{"Operate" LINK aowcu_Operate}                       @{"Op & Exit" LINK aowcu_Operate}|
     +-----------------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE aowcu_DrawLine "Draw Line"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW LINE@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Curve Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the line tool is used when drawing the cruve.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowcu_DrawFree "Draw Freehand"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DRAW FREEHAND@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Curve Window)@{ui}

When this is activated the freehand tool is used when drawing the curve.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowcu_Curve "Filter Curve"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}FILTER CURVE@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Curve Window)@{ui}

This is the filter curve display. Bass is shown to the left and treble
to the right.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowcu_Operate "Operate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OPERATE (& EXIT)@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Curve Window)@{ui}

Applies the current filter on the analyzed data, but the sample will
@{b}not@{ub} be recalculated.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aow_RemNoise "Rem Noise"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}REM NOISE (REMOVE NOISE)@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option Window)@{ui}

This is a very useful function, which can remove noise from your samples.
It will only remove "random" noise, and thus @{b}not@{ub} harmonic noise,
like a tone. Unwanted tones can easily be removed by hand by using the
@{"Scale" LINK aow_Scale} function. To see a harmonic tone, just use the
right amplification factor in the display, and it will appear as a vertical
line.

      @{b}REM NOISE@{ub}
     +------------------+
     |NOISE LEVEL 1/100%|
     |      @{"034" LINK aowrn_NoiseLevel}        |
     |@{"Operate" LINK aowrn_Operate}@{"Op & Exit" LINK aowrn_Operate}|
     +------------------+

If this function is used in a good way, you may achieve a result like this:
@{"Sample Before filter" LINK AnalyzeNoise.8svx/main} @{"Sample After Filter" LINK AnalyzeRemNoise.8svx/main}

@ENDNODE

@NODE aowrn_NoiseLevel "Noise Level"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}NOISE LEVEL@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Rem Noise Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the level of the noise to be removed. If a sample is
very noisy, a higher level should be used. The number corresponds to percents
of percents of a maximum amplitude curve. If you use a too high level the 
sample may sound strange. Just keep trying until it sounds good.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowrn_Operate "Operate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OPERATE (& EXIT)@{ub} @{i}(Scale Option -> Scale Window)@{ui}

Removes the noise from the current range in the analyzed data, but the sample
will @{b}not@{ub} be recalculated.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aow_Display "Display"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DISPLAY@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option Window)@{ui}

This is a window displaying the current analyzed data.
The data is splitted into analyze blocks, which each corresponds to 256
bytes of the sample. One block is drawn in one line. Bass is shown to the
left of the display, and treble on the right.

      @{b}DISPLAY@{ub}
     +----------------------------------------------+
     |@{"Show All" LINK aowdi_ShowAll}@{"Show Range" LINK aowdi_ShowRange}@{"Zoom Out" LINK aowdi_ZoomOut}       @{" " LINK aowdi_Right}@{" " LINK aowdi_Left}@{"  " LINK aowdi_Lines}@{"  " LINK aowdi_HiddenLines}|
     |+--++------------------------------------++--+|
     ||  ||                                    ||  ||
     ||  ||                                    ||  ||
     ||  ||                                    ||@{" " LINK aowdi_Position}||
     ||  ||                                    ||  ||
     ||@{" " LINK aowdi_Amplification}||                                    ||  ||
     ||  ||              @{"Display" LINK aowdi_Display}              ||  ||
     ||  ||                                    ||  ||
     ||  ||                                    ||  ||
     ||  ||                                    ||  ||
     ||  ||                                    ||  ||
     |+--++------------------------------------++--+|
     +----------------------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE aowdi_ShowAll "Show All"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}SHOW ALL@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Display Window)@{ui}

Shows the whole sample analyze.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowdi_ShowRange "Show Range"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}SHOW RANGE@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Display Window)@{ui}

Shows the current range, if present.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowdi_ZoomOut "Zoom Out"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}ZOOM OUT@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Display Window)@{ui}

Shows a bit more of the sample analyze.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowdi_Right "Right"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}RIGHT@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Display Window)@{ui}

When this is active, the sample will be plotted so that you can look at it
from the right.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowdi_Left "Left"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}LEFT@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Display Window)@{ui}

Opposite to @{"Right" LINK aowdi_Right}...
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowdi_Lines "Use Lines"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}USE LINES@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Display Window)@{ui}

When this is active, the sample will be plotted using lines (this option
is much faster than @{"Use Hidden Lines" LINK aowdi_HiddenLines}).
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowdi_HiddenLines "Use HiddenLines"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}USE HIDDEN LINES@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Display Window)@{ui}

When this is active, the sample will be plotted using hidden lines (this
option is much slower than @{"Use Lines" LINK aowdi_Lines}).
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowdi_Amplification "Amplification"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}AMPLIFICATION@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Display Window)@{ui}

The higher this slider is set, the more the sample will be amplified
when it's plotted it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowdi_Position "Position"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}POSITION@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Display Window)@{ui}

This slider marks the current position in the sample analyze, in case you
don't show all of it at once.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aowdi_Display "Display"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DISPLAY@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option -> Display Window)@{ui}

This is where the sample analyze data is plotted. To mark a range, use your
mouse. It might be a bit hard to hit the right spot in the beginning, but
you'll learn. 

@{i}How to interpret the display:@{ui}
If you want to remove a certain sound from a sample, it is important to be
able to see exactly where that sound is in the display. Here are some
examples:

@{b}Bass drums:@{ub} Are most often shown as sharp "mountains", quickly moving from
the center of the display to the left edge.
@{"Example Picture" LINK AnalyzeDisplayBD.ilbm/main} @{"Sounds like this" LINK AnalyzeDisplayBD.8svx/main}

@{b}Tones, harmonic sounds:@{ub} Shown as "mountains" going from top to bottom
vertically, with "valleys" in between.
@{"Example Picture" LINK AnalyzeDisplayBell.ilbm/main} @{"Sounds like this" LINK AnalyzeDisplayBell.8svx/main}

@{b}Unwanted harmonic sampler noise:@{ub} Looks like a tone, often in the far right
of the display. Use a high amplifiaction level to see them.
@{"Example Picture" LINK AnalyzeDisplayAmazing.ilbm/main} @{"Sounds like this" LINK AnalyzeDisplayAmazing.8svx/main}

@ENDNODE

@NODE aow_ReAnalyze "ReAnalyze"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}REANALYZE@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option Window)@{ui}

When pressing this, the current sample will be reanalyzed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE aow_MakeSound "Make Sound"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}MAKE SOUND@{ub} @{i}(Analyze Option Window)@{ui}

This is the same function which is executed when playing the sound: The
analyzed data is converted to a sample again. This will not be done
automagically when closing this window, so remeber to do it yourself.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Delta "Delta"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}DELTA@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

      @{b}DELTA@{ub}
     +--------------------+
     |Cut Frequency       |
     | @{"001" LINK dow_Cut}         @{"Range" LINK dow_Range}|
     |@{"Operate" LINK dow_Operate}  @{"Op & Exit" LINK dow_Operate}|
     +--------------------+
@ENDNODE

@NODE dow_Cut "Cut Frequency"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}CUT FREQUENCY@{ub} @{i}(Delta Option Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the sample cut frequence. The filter will cut this
frequency and all multiples of it, so it may sound strange when filtering
low frequencies.
@ENDNODE

@NODE dow_Range "Range"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}RANGE@{ub} @{i}(Delta Option Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the the Cut Frequency so that a sinewave with the
same period as the range will be cut.
@ENDNODE

@NODE dow_Operate "Operate"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}OPERATE (& EXIT)@{ub} @{i}(Delta Option Window)@{ui}

This will apply the current settings on the sample.
@{i}Note:@{ui} If range is present, the delta filter will only affect it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Boost1 "Boost 1"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}BOOST 1@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

Can make relatively "sharp" sounds sound even worse...
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Boost2 "Boost 2"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}BOOST 2@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

This filter can actually "anti filter" samples, i.e make the sound clearer.
If you use it more, it makes the samples really "sharp".
@ENDNODE

@NODE sew_Cancel "Cancel"
@TOC SampleEditWindow
@{b}Cancel@{ub} @{i}(Sample Edit Window)@{ui}

Forgets the 16 bit sample, and returns to the old 8 bit sample.
@ENDNODE

@NODE DiskOperationWindow "Disk Operation Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}DISK OPERATION WINDOW:@{ub}
This is the menu which contains all the disk operation functions (load, save).

      @{b}DISK@{ub}
     +------------+
     |Module:     |
     |@{"Load...    " LINK dw_LoadModule}|
     |@{"Save...    " LINK dw_SaveModule}|
     |Load From   |
     |Module:     |
     |@{"Pattern... " LINK dw_LoadFromModule}|
     |@{"Track...   " LINK dw_LoadFromModule}|
     |@{"Sample...  " LINK dw_LoadFromModule}|
     |Sample:     |
     |@{"Load...    " LINK dw_LoadSample}|
     |@{"Save...    " LINK dw_SaveSample}|
     |Settings:   |
     |@{"Load       " LINK dw_LoadSettings}|
     |@{"Save...    " LINK dw_SaveSettings}|
     |Sample List:|
     |@{"Use        " LINK dw_UseSampleList}|
     |@{"Load       " LINK dw_LoadSampleList}|
     |@{"Temp...    " LINK dw_TempSampleList}|
     |@{"Add...     " LINK dw_AddSampleToList}|
     |@{"Save...    " LINK dw_SaveSampleList}|
     +------------+
	
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_LoadModule "Load Module"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}LOAD MODULE@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Displays a file requester, in which you should pick the desired module.
If you load a new module, the old one will be lost. 
Quadra Composer 2.1 supports IFF @{"EMOD" LINK Words} and NoiseTracker modules.
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_SaveModule "Save Module"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}SAVE MODULE@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Displays a requester asking which module format you want to use. Default,
and the best, choise is "IFF @{"EMOD" LINK Words}".
"NT" is short for the other choice, "NoiseTracker".
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_LoadFromModule "Load From Module"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}LOAD FROM MODULE@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Lets you pick an IFF @{"EMOD" LINK Words}. The patterns / samples of the
module will be displayed in a window. To load a pattern / track / sample on
top of the current pattern / track /sample, just double click on it.
In the option window, you can turn Load Samples on / off. Load Sample mean
that all the samples in the loaded pattern / track will be added to the
module, unless you don't already have a sample with the same name.
A little tip: You can build up "clip" modules with e.g drumtracks, which
you can include later in your music.
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_LoadSample "Load Sample"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}LOAD SAMPLE@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Loads a sample, IFF 8SVX or raw.
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_SaveSample "Save Sample"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}SAVE SAMPLE@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Lets you pick a file format, IFF 8SVX or raw, in which the sample will
be saved.
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_LoadSettings "Load Settings"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}LOAD SETTINGS@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Loads your previously saved settings from the file 
"ENVARC:QuadraComposer.prefs".
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_SaveSettings "Save Settings"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}SAVE SETTINGS@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Saves your settings.
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_UseSampleList "Use Sample List"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}USE SAMPLE LIST@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Displays the sample list window. A sample list is just a list in which
names and paths of samples are stored. This is very useful if you have
loaded all your sample disks to the list. You can then easily find THAT
sample you're looking for. Another advantage is that you don't have to wait
for the computer to read the directory every time. To load a sample from
the list, just double click on it. If the disk is not in your drives, the
computer will ask for it as usual.
@ENDNODE 

@NODE dw_LoadSampleList "Load Sample List"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}LOAD SAMPLE LIST@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Loads your previously saved sample list file "s:QuadraComposer.samplelist".
The sample list file is actually an ASCII text, which you can edit from
any text editor.
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_TempSampleList "Load Temporary Sample List"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}LOAD TEMPORARY SAMPLE LIST@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Asks for a directory, which will be read and used as a temporary sample
list. This function is used if you want to load more than one sample from
a disk which is not in your sample list.
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_AddSampleToList "Add Sample To List"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}ADD SAMPLE TO LIST@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Displays a multiselect file requester, from which you can choose one, or
by pressing shift, more, samples to be added to the current sample list.
@ENDNODE

@NODE dw_SaveSampleList "Save Sample List"
@TOC DiskOperationWindow
@{b}SAVE SAMPLE LIST@{ub} @{i}(Disk Operation Window)@{ui}

Saves the current sample list to the file "s:QuadraComposer.samplelist".
@ENDNODE

@NODE MixerWindow "Mixer Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}MIXER WINDOW:@{ub}

This window is used to mix your patterns together to a song.

      @{b}MIXER@{ub}
     +-----------------------------+
     |Pattern:                Pos: |
     |+---------------------+ +---+|
     ||                     | |   ||
     ||                     | |   ||
     ||                     | |   ||
     ||                     | |   ||
     ||     @{"Pattern List" LINK mw_PatternList}   | | @{"P" LINK mw_PositionList}||
     ||                     | |   ||
     ||                     | |   ||
     ||                     | |   ||
     ||                     | |   ||
     |+---------------------+ +---+|
     |@{"P" LINK mw_Paste}@{"C" LINK mw_Clear}                         |
     +-----------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE mw_PatternList "Pattern List"
@TOC MixerWindow
@{b}PATTERN LIST@{ub} @{i}(Mixer Window)@{ui}

Here are the 256 patterns plus numbers listed. If you click on a pattern,
it will be marked, and if you drag it, you can insert the patternnumber
in the position list.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mw_PositionList "Position List"
@TOC MixerWindow
@{b}POSITION LIST@{ub} @{i}(Mixer Window)@{ui}

Here are the <songlength> positions listed. Just like the pattern list, you
can mark positions, and move them around by dragging with the mouse.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mw_Paste "Paste Pattern"
@TOC MixerWindow
@{b}PASTE PATTERN@{ub} @{i}(Mixer Window)@{ui}

Inserts the marked pattern number in the position list, at the marked
position.
@ENDNODE

@NODE mw_Clear "Clear Position"
@TOC MixerWindow
@{b}CLEAR POSITION@{ub} @{i}(Mixer Window)@{ui}

Deletes the marked position.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TextWindow "Text Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}TEXT WINDOW:@{ub}

This is just a tiny text window.

      @{b}TEXT@{ub}
     +--------------------------+
     | @{"Groovier funk           " LINK tw_SongName}|
     | @{"©1994 A. Dent           " LINK tw_ComposerName}|
     | @{"FunkGuitar 3            " LINK tw_SampleName}|
     | @{"Intro fade in           " LINK tw_PatternName}|
     | @{"OK!                     " LINK tw_StatusLine}|
     | @{"123876 (hex 1e3e4) bytes" LINK tw_ModuleLength}|
     +--------------------------+
@ENDNODE

@NODE tw_SongName "Song Name"
@TOC TextWindow
@{b}SONG NAME@{ub} @{i}(Text Window)@{ui}

This is where the name of the current module is displayed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE tw_ComposerName "Composer Name"
@TOC TextWindow
@{b}COMPOSER NAME@{ub} @{i}(Text Window)@{ui}

This is where the name of the composer of the current module is
displayed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE tw_SampleName "Sample Name"
@TOC TextWindow
@{b}SAMPLE NAME@{ub} @{i}(Text Window)@{ui}

This is where the name of the current sample is displayed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE tw_PatternName "Pattern Name"
@TOC TextWindow
@{b}PATTERN NAME@{ub} @{i}(Text Window)@{ui}

This is where the name of the current pattern is displayed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE tw_StatusLine "Status Line"
@TOC TextWindow
@{b}STATUS LINE@{ub} @{i}(Text Window)@{ui}

This is where all error messages and other status messages are
displayed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE tw_ModuleLength "Module Length"
@TOC TextWindow
@{b}MODULE LENGTH@{ub} @{i}(Text Window)@{ui}

This is where the length of the current module is displayed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE NoteEditWindow "Note Edit Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}NOTE EDIT WINDOW:@{ub}

Here are some note and track editing functions.

      @{b}NOTE EDIT@{ub}
     +----------------------------+
     |Track:                      |
     |@{"Expand       " LINK new_Expand}@{"Clear...     " LINK new_Clear}|
     |@{"Swap...      " LINK new_Swap}@{"Exg.Smp...   " LINK new_ExgSmp}|
     |ACTIVE SMP:   ALL:          |
     |TRACK: PATT:  TRACK: PATT:  |
     |@{"Note |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Note |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Note |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Note |" LINK new_Transpose}|
     |@{"Note |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Note |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Note |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Note |" LINK new_Transpose}|
     |@{"Oct. |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Oct. |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Oct. |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Oct. |" LINK new_Transpose}|
     |@{"Oct. |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Oct. |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Oct. |" LINK new_Transpose}@{"Oct. |" LINK new_Transpose}|
     +----------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE new_Expand "Expand Track"
@TOC NoteEditWindow
@{b}EXPAND TRACK@{ub} @{i}(Note Edit Window)@{ui}

This function doubles the space between notes in the current track,
starting from the current line.
@ENDNODE

@NODE new_Swap "Swap Tracks"
@TOC NoteEditWindow
@{b}SWAP TRACKS@{ub} @{i}(Note Edit Window)@{ui}

Swaps the active track with another.
@ENDNODE

@NODE new_Clear "Clear Track"
@TOC NoteEditWindow
@{b}CLEAR TRACK@{ub} @{i}(Note Edit Window)@{ui}

Clears the current track from the current line.
@ENDNODE

@NODE new_ExgSmp "Exchange Samples"
@TOC NoteEditWindow
@{b}EXG. SMP (EXCHANGE SAMPLES)@{ub} @{i}(Note Edit Window)@{ui}

Replaces the current sample number in the track with a new one.
@ENDNODE

@NODE new_Transpose "Transposing"
@TOC NoteEditWindow
@{b}TRANSPOSING@{ub} @{i}(Note Edit Window)@{ui}

These gadgets lets you transpose notes up or down. Active sample means
that only notes with the active sample number will be affected.
@ENDNODE

@NODE SpectrumAnalyzerWindow "Spectrum Analyzer Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}SPECTRUM ANALYZER WINDOW:@{ub}

This is a little window showing a spectrum analysis of the sounds being
played. It works remarkably well, although it doesn't use FFT. If you size
the window to maximum size, the spectrum analyser will change, and get
bigger (and slower).
When the analyser is small, each line represents 1/4 of an octave.
Otherwise the each line represents 1 note.
@ENDNODE

@NODE QuadrascopeWindow "Quadrascope Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}QUADRASCOPE WINDOW:@{ub}

This is also a way of showing the samples being played. If the window is
small, four "scopes" are being displayed, one for each voice. Otherwise
only one, including all voices is displayed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE SplitWindow "Split Keyboard Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}SPLIT KEYBOARD WINDOW:@{ub}

This is an editor used to put samples in different spots on the keyboard.
E.g, if you're using a set of drums, you may want to put one on C-1,
one on D-1, and a third on E-1, or maybe you want a multisampled piano.


      @{b}SPLIT@{ub}
     +-----------------+
     |Split  @{"Add...   " LINK skw_Add}|
     |  @{"01" LINK skw_SplitNumber}  @{"Delete..." LINK skw_Delete}|
     |From     Smp +--+|
     |+-----------+|  ||
     ||           ||  ||
     ||           ||  ||
     ||  @{"Display" LINK skw_Display} ||  ||
     ||           ||  ||
     ||           ||  ||
     |+-----------++--+|
     |From        Base |
     |  @{"C3" LINK skw_From}         @{"C3" LINK skw_Base}|
     |@{"Add Part        " LINK skw_AddPart}|
     +-----------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE skw_Add "Add Split"
@TOC SplitWindow
@{b}ADD SPLIT@{ub} @{i}(Split Keyboard Window)@{ui}

Adds a new keyboard split to the list.
@ENDNODE

@NODE skw_Delete "Delete Split"
@TOC SplitWindow
@{b}DELETE SPLIT@{ub} @{i}(Split Keyboard Window)@{ui}

Deletes the current keyboard split from the list.
@ENDNODE

@NODE skw_SplitNumber "Split Number"
@TOC SplitWindow
@{b}SPLIT NUMBER@{ub} @{i}(Split Keyboard Window)@{ui}

This gadget is duplicated, it can be found in the @{"Main Note Window" LINK MainNoteWindow}.
When this is set to off, the current sample will be used on all keys.
Otherwise, when a key is pressed, the program scans the current split, to
find the first "part" with "From" less or equal to the current key.
If no sample is found, the current sample will be used.
@ENDNODE

@NODE skw_Display "Split Display"
@TOC SplitWindow
@{b}SPLIT DISPLAY@{ub} @{i}(Split Keyboard Window)@{ui}

     From Base Smp
     C1   C3   01
     D1   C3   02
     E1   C3   03

The example above will play sample 01 when one of the keys C1 or C#1 is
pressed, using pitch C3. When one of the keys D1 or D#1 is pressed 02 will
be played, and so on.
If G1 is pressed, sample 03 will be played, using pitch (G1-E1) + C3 = D#3.
@ENDNODE

@NODE skw_From "From Key"
@TOC SplitWindow
@{b}FROM KEY@{ub} @{i}(Split Keyboard Window)@{ui}

This value will be stored in the key column when pressing @{"Add Part" LINK skw_AddPart}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE skw_Base "Base"
@TOC SplitWindow
@{b}BASE@{ub} @{i}(Split Keyboard Window)@{ui}

This value will be stored in the base column when pressing @{"Add Part" LINK skw_AddPart}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE skw_AddPart "Add Part"
@TOC SplitWindow
@{b}ADD PART@{ub} @{i}(Split Keyboard Window)@{ui}

This function will add a new line to the current split, using the
current sample, the "From" and the "Base" values. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE MIDIInWindow "MIDI In Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}MIDI IN WINDOW:@{ub}

If you've got a synth and a MIDI interface, you're able to play the notes
on it instead of using the Amiga keyboard. You might also want to use the
Amiga as a sample module in a bigger MIDI and synth system.

      @{b}MIDI In@{ub}
     +-------------------------------+
     |MIDICh. Split Voice Vel.  N.Off|
     |1  @{"01" LINK miw_Chan}    @{"02" LINK miw_Split}   @{"??" LINK miw_Voice}   @{"08" LINK miw_Vel}   @{"Of" LINK miw_NOff}|
     |2  @{"04" LINK miw_Chan}    @{"01" LINK miw_Split}   @{"??" LINK miw_Voice}   @{"10" LINK miw_Vel}   @{"On" LINK miw_NOff}|
     |3  @{"Of" LINK miw_Chan}    @{"Of" LINK miw_Split}   @{"Of" LINK miw_Voice}   @{"00" LINK miw_Vel}   @{"Of" LINK miw_NOff}|
     |4  @{"Of" LINK miw_Chan}    @{"Of" LINK miw_Split}   @{"Of" LINK miw_Voice}   @{"00" LINK miw_Vel}   @{"Of" LINK miw_NOff}|
     |Oct.  Enable                   |
     | @{"04" LINK miw_Oct}    @{"On" LINK miw_Enable}                    |
     +-------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE miw_Chan "MIDI In Channel"
@TOC MIDIInWindow
@{b}MIDI IN CHANNEL@{ub} @{i}(MIDI In Window)@{ui}

This is where you set which MIDI channel the program should reconize.
@ENDNODE

@NODE miw_Split "Split"
@TOC MIDIInWindow
@{b}SPLIT@{ub} @{i}(MIDI In Window)@{ui}

When a MIDI message is recieved, this split will be used to play a sample.
If this is set to off, the current sample will be used.
@ENDNODE

@NODE miw_Voice "Voice"
@TOC MIDIInWindow
@{b}VOICE@{ub} @{i}(MIDI In Window)@{ui}

This is the voice the sample will be played on. If this is set to
off, the current voice will be used. If it is set to "??" the first free
voice will be used.
@ENDNODE

@NODE miw_Vel "Velocity"
@TOC MIDIInWindow
@{b}VEL. (VELOCITY)@{ub} @{i}(MIDI In Window)@{ui}

This determines the velocity sensivity. If it's set to 16 (@{"hex" LINK DecHex} 10)
the velocity from the MIDI keyboard will be used, and if it's set to 0
the default sample volume will be used. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE miw_NOff "Note Off"
@TOC MIDIInWindow
@{b}N. OFF (NOTE OFF)@{ub} @{i}(MIDI In Window)@{ui}

This determines whether the program should recognize note off messages.
If this is on, and a note off message is recieved, the current sample will
be cut.  
@ENDNODE

@NODE miw_Oct "Octave"
@TOC MIDIInWindow
@{b}OCT. (OCTAVE)@{ub} @{i}(MIDI In Window)@{ui}

This is where you set the base octave on the MIDI keyboard. If this
is set to 3, the C-1 will be on C in the third octave on the MIDI keyboard.
@ENDNODE

@NODE miw_Enable "Enable"
@TOC MIDIInWindow
@{b}ENABLE@{ub} @{i}(MIDI In Window)@{ui}

Do you want MIDI in to be in action?
@ENDNODE

@NODE PreferencesWindow "Preferences Window"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}PREFERENCES WINDOW:@{ub}

      @{b}PREFERENCES@{ub}
     +------------------------------------+
     |@{"Screen Mode... " LINK prw_ScreenMode}Big Scope Accuracy: |
     |@{"Palette...     " LINK prw_Palette}        @{"200" LINK prw_BigScopeAcc}        |
     |   Hex @{"    0" LINK prw_HexDec}   Big Spect Accuracy: |
     |   Dec @{"    0" LINK prw_HexDec}     @{"003" LINK prw_BigSpectAcc}              |
     |Fake                                |
     |Chipmem   RMB       Fast            |
     |(ECS)     Activate  Graphics        |
     |  @{"On" LINK prw_FakeChip}       @{"Of" LINK prw_RMBActivate}       @{"Of" LINK prw_FastGfx}           |
     +------------------------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE prw_ScreenMode "Screen Mode"
@TOC PreferencesWindow
@{b}SCREEN MODE@{ub} @{i}(Preferences Window)@{ui}

Lets you pick a screen mode, minimum 640x256 pixels.
@ENDNODE

@NODE prw_Palette "Palette"
@TOC PreferencesWindow
@{b}SCREEN MODE@{ub} @{i}(Preferences Window)@{ui}

Lets you adjust the palette.
@ENDNODE

@NODE prw_BigScopeAcc "Big Scope Accuracy"
@TOC PreferencesWindow
@{b}BIG SCOPE ACCURACY@{ub} @{i}(Preferences Window)@{ui}

Sets how many pixels should be displayed per voice in the big scope.
@ENDNODE

@NODE prw_BigSpectAcc "Big Spect Accuracy"
@TOC PreferencesWindow
@{b}BIG SPECT ACCURACY@{ub} @{i}(Preferences Window)@{ui}

Sets how many frequencies the analyser should try to find.
@ENDNODE

@NODE prw_HexDec "Hexadecimal - Decimal"
@TOC PreferencesWindow
@{b}HEXADECIMAL - DECIMAL@{ub} @{i}(Preferences Window)@{ui}

This is a translator from @{"hexadecimal" LINK DecHex} to decimal and decimal to hexadecimal.
Just type the number in the gadget and press <enter>.
@ENDNODE

@NODE prw_FakeChip "Fake Chipmem"
@TOC PreferencesWindow
@{b}Fake Chipmem@{ub} @{i}(Preferences Window)@{ui}

If this is on, Quadra Composer will try to use the internal fast memory expansion on A500's as
chipmem. This will not work if you don't have at least ECS.
@ENDNODE

@NODE prw_RMBActivate "RMB Activate"
@TOC PreferencesWindow
@{b}RMB ACTIVATE@{ub} @{i}(Preferences Window)@{ui}

If this is on, you'll be able to activate windows with the right mouse button.
@ENDNODE

@NODE prw_FastGfx "Fast Graphics"
@TOC PreferencesWindow
@{b}FAST GRAPHICS@{ub} @{i}(Preferences Window)@{ui}

Fast graphics means that the window graphics is drawn by internal _fast_ routines in Quadra
Composer. If it's off graphics.library will be used. Note: If you have a graphics card, like
Merlin, Picasso, Retina etc. you _must_ turn this function off!
@ENDNODE

@NODE KeyboardCommands "Keyboard Commands"
@TOC Main_Operation
@{b}KEYBOARD COMMANDS@{ub}
Many of these commands can also be found in the menus, using Amiga standard
(amiga + key).
The main keyboard is used for entering notes.
(Am. layout)
     2 3   6 7 8   9
    Q W R T Y U I O P       Higher octave
    \___/
        \_________ The same notes
                  \___
                  /   \
     S D   G H J   L ;
    Z X C V B N M , . /     Lower octave

The default lower octave is 2.


@{b}MISC KEYBOARD COMMANDS.@{ub}
RIGHT SHIFT     Record song.
RIGHT ALT       Play song.
RIGHT AMIGA     Play pattern.
<               Turn off all samples. (Not available on some Am.
                                       keyboards.)
SPACE           Toggle editing on/off.
RETURN          Insert blank row in track.
A-RETURN        Insert blank row in pattern (all tracks).
C-RETURN        Insert blank row in track (effect cmd only).
BACKSPACE       Delete previous row and move rest of the track upwards.
A-BACKSP.                          -"-                   pattern  -"-
C-BACKSP.       As BACKSPACE but only effect command.
DELETE          Delete note/effect of the current track, row.
S-DELETE        Delete note+effect        -"-
TAB             Move cursor to next track (right).
S-TAB                 -"-      prev  -"-   left
F1              Set lower octave to "1"
F2              Set lower octave to "2"
F3              Cut block to buffer.
S-F3            Cut entire track (notes only).
A-F3            Cut entire pattern (notes only).
F4              As F3, but Copy instead.
F5              Paste buffer.
S-F5            Paste from top of track (notes only).
A-F5            Paste from "top left corner" of track (notes only).
F6-F10          Move to "bookmark", default are 00/10/20/30/40
S-(F6-F10)      Set "bookmark".
A-(F6-F10)      Play pattern from "bookmark".
C-(F6-F10)      Record        -"-
S-(1-9)         Store current effectcommand in effectbuffer 1-9.
A-(1-9)         Paste effectbuffer 1-9 into current cursorpos.
C-(1-9)         Set editskip to 1-9. Ie the number of rows the editor
                jumps after a note is struck.
A-(Z,X,C,V)     Toggle voice 1-4 on/off
A-MINUS (Main keyboard, Am. layout)
                Copy previous effect command and decrease its
                argument.
A-PLUS (Main keyboard, Am. layout)
                Copy prev. fx cmd and increase its arg.
A-\             Copy prev. fx cmd.

C-A             Toggle current voice on/off.
C-C             Copy block.
C-D             Clear block.
C-E             Expand track.
C-F             Toggle filter on/off.
C-G             Toggle AutoEcho on/off.
C-I             Paste buffer.
C-K             Clear to end of track.
C-M             Toggle MultiMode on/off
C-P             Paste buffer.
C-Q             Turn all voices on.
C-R             Restore "bookmarks".
C-T             Swap tracks.
C-V             Paste buffer.
C-X             Cut block.

Am-M            Mark block
A-M             Mark block

@{b}ARROW KEY OPERATION@{ub}
UP              Move cursor up.
DOWN            Move cursor down
LEFT            Move cursor left.
RIGHT           Move cursor right.
S-UP            Move cursor up 8 rows.
S-DOWN          Move cursor down 8 rows.
S-LEFT          Decrease position.
S-RIGHT         Increase position.
C-LEFT          Decrease sample number.
C-RIGHT         Increase sample number.
A-LEFT          Decrease current pattern number.
A-RIGHT         Increase current pattern number.

@{b}NUMERIC KEYPAD (Not available on A600. ;-(@{ub}
+-+-+-+-+
|1|2|3|4|
+-+-+-+-+
|5|6|7|8|
+-+-+-+-+
|9|A|B|C|
+-+-+-+-+
|D|E|F|0|
+-+-+-+ |
|   | | |
+---+-+-+
 ^   ^
 |   \_ Increase sample number by @{"hex" LINK DecHex} 10.
 \_____ Decrease         -"-


@ENDNODE

@NODE Basics "Basics"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}BASICS:@{ub}
Quadra Composer works with four voices (limited by the Amiga), which
are represented by the four tracks you can see in the main note window.
These four tracks of a certain length form a pattern. Up to 256 patterns
can form a song, and finally, a song plus all samples form a module.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Notes "Notes"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}NOTES:@{ub}
The first space in every line of a track is reserved for the note.

     C#101000
     \_/
       \__ The note.

The note range is from C-1 (lowest) to B 3 (highest). Each time the track
finds a note when playing, it will play the sample connected to it, using
the note frequency. But, it's not like a synthesizier, since the sample will
not stop when you release the key. In keeps playing until the entire sample
is played, or until you play another sample in the sample voice. If you
want to cut a sample before it's completely played, you'll have to use the
volume effect command (see chapter 2.1).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SampleNumber "Sample Number"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}SAMPLE NUMBER:@{ub}
To each note there must be a sample number, so that Quadra Composer will
know what sound to play.

     C#101000
        \/
         \__ The sample number.

The sample number will automatically be written when typing a note.

Using this little knowledge you can make your first modules. If you want to
make the more advanced, check out the next chapter.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PatternsPositions "Patterns & Positions"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}PATTERNS & POSITIONS:@{ub}
When you've made some patterns, you can mix 'em together to a song, either
by using the Pos. and Patt. gadgets, or by using the mixer.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Basics "Basics"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}EFFECT COMMANDS:@{ub}
The effect command is the last three (3) digits of each line of a
track.

| C 101xyz |
  ^^^^^^^^
  \_/\/\_/____ Effect command
    \ \_______ Sample number
     \________ Note.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Arpeggio "Arpeggio"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command 0yz: ARPEGGIO:@{ub}
Arpeggio is a rapid pitch change. The pitch changes between the
played note and the notes Y resp. Z halftones higher.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PitchSlideUp "Pitch Slide, Up"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command 1yz: PITCH SLIDE, UP:@{ub}
Slides the pitch up YZ halftones. The resulting pitch cannot be
higher than the highest possible pitch (B 3).

@ENDNODE

@NODE PitchSlideDown "Pitch Slide, Down"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command 2yz: PITCH SLIDE, DOWN:@{ub}
Slides the pitch down YZ halftones. The resulting pitch cannot be
lower than the lowest possible pitch (C 1).

@ENDNODE

@NODE TonePortamento "Tone Portamento"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command 3yz: TONE PORTAMENTO:@{ub}
Slides the pitch up/down to played the note at YZ halftones per
frame. The effect must be reactivated on each row. If YZ=00 then the
last YZ will be used.

| C 101000 |
| C 201302 |
|    00300 |
|    00300 |
| ...      |

When the desired pitch is reached, the effect will not do anything.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Vibrato "Vibrato"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command 4yz: VIBRATO:@{ub}
Makes a vibrato effect on the sample played. The command must be
reactivated on each row. Y is the speed of the vibrato and Z is the
depth. If an argument is "0" then the previous value used will be
used.

| C 101445 |        +-------------------------------------+
|    00406 |     <--| Makes the vibrato deeper and deeper |
|    00407 |        +-------------------------------------+
|    00408 |
|    00409 |

@ENDNODE

@NODE VolSlideTonePort "Volume Slide + Sustained Tone Portamento
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command 5yz: VOLUME SLIDE + SUSTAINED TONE PORTAMENTO:@{ub}
Adds a volume slide to a tone portamento. The portamento must be
initialized with the [3yz] effect before this effect can be used. The
Y argument represents the volume increase rate and Z the decrease.

| C 101000 |        +--------------------------------------+
| C 201305 |     <--| Continues the portamento and slides  |
|    00501 |        | the volume down                      |
|    00501 |        +--------------------------------------+
|...       |

@ENDNODE

@NODE VolSlideVibrato "Volume Slide + Sustained Vibrato"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command 6yz: VOLUME SLIDE + SUSTAINED VIBRATO:@{ub}
Similar to command [5yz], see above. The vibrato should be
initialized before using this command.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Tremolo "Tremolo"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command 7yz: TREMOLO:@{ub}
Creates a volume vibrato. The speed is set with the argument Y and
the depth with Z. If an argument is "0" then the last value for that
argument is used.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SetSampleOffset "Set Sample Offset"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command 9yz: SET SAMPLE OFFSET:@{ub}
Used only when a note is played, to skip a bit into the sample. The
argument YZ is multiplied with @{"hex" LINK DecHex} 200 and that many bytes of the
sample are skipped.

| C 101923 |     <--| Skips @{"hex" LINK DecHex} 23 * 200 = 4600 bytes |

NOTE: This differs from the NT-format, where the offset was @{"hex" LINK DecHex}
YZ*100.

@ENDNODE

@NODE VolumeSlide "Volume Slide"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command Ayz: VOLUME SLIDE:@{ub}
Slides the volume up at the speed set by Y or down at the speed set
by Z. The effect must be reactivated on each row.

| C 207A20 |        +-----------------------+
|    00A20 |     <--| Slides the volume up. |
| ...      |        +-----------------------+

@ENDNODE

@NODE PositionJump "Position Jump"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command Byz: POSITION JUMP:@{ub}
Skips the rest of the current pattern (It's a good idea to pull the
length down to save some bytes of memory...) and jumps to position
@{"hex" LINK DecHex} YZ.

NOTE: This differs from the NT-format, where the argument to this
effect was given as a decimal number.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SetVolume "Set Volume"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command Cyz: SET VOLUME:@{ub}
Set the volume for a channel. The argument YZ sets the new volume.
The volume must be between @{"hex" LINK DecHex} 0 and 40.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PatternBreak "Pattern Break"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command Dyz: PATTERN BREAK:@{ub}
Skips the rest of the current pattern (see command Byz) and the first
YZ rows of the next pattern (YZ should not exceed the length of the
next pattern).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SetSpeed "Set Speed / Tempo"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command Fyz: SET SPEED/TEMPO:@{ub}
Sets the speed of a pattern (and the ones that follow...) if the
argument YZ is less than or equal to @{"hex" LINK DecHex} 1F or the tempo if YZ is
higher than @{"hex" LINK DecHex} 1F.

The speed is normally the number of picture frames or vertical blanks
(1/50 second PAL or 1/60 second NTSC) to wait between each row of a
pattern. The default speed is 06, ie 0.12 seconds (PAL) or 125 beats
per minute.

If the tempo is set QuadraComposer will switch from VBL timing (125
@{"BPM" LINK Words}, PAL) to CIA timing. The default tempo is @{"hex" LINK DecHex} 7D (125 @{"BPM" LINK Words},
again). The tempo rating assumes a default speed setting.

TECHNOTE: If the tempo is set to anything else than 7D, then the
level 6 CIA interrupt must be used. If the tempo is set high then the
replay takes more time each frame (the replay interrupt also will get
out of phase with the screen refresh, so worst case time consumption
can get high (or at least unpredictable) even when using lower tempo,
check the replay routine...).

@ENDNODE

@NODE SetFilter "SetFilter"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command E0z: SET FILTER:@{ub}
Used to switch the internal audio filter on or off. If Z is "0" the
filter is switched on and if Z is "1" the filter is switched off.

NOTE: Some old amiga's don't have this feature.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FinePitchSlideUp "Fine Pitch Slide, Up"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command E1z: FINE PITCHSLIDE, UP:@{ub}
Slide the pitch up a little bit, Z is simply added to the pitch.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FinePitchSlideDown "Fine Pitch Slide, Down"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command E2z: FINE PITCHSLIDE, DOWN:@{ub}
Slide the pitch down a little bit, Z is simply subtracted from the pitch.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SetGlissando "Set Glissando"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command E3z: SET GLISSANDO:@{ub}
Turn glissando on (Z = "1") or off (Z = "0"). Glissando is used with
portamento. If it is turned on, then the portamento will be done
halftone by halftone, like "walking" up or down the piano.

TECHNOTE: This effect can use up a lot of time, check the replay
routine...

@ENDNODE

@NODE SetVibratoWaveform "Set Vibrato Waveform"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command E4z: SET VIBRATO WAVEFORM:@{ub}
Simply selects the waveform used for vibrato effects. Z=0     Use
sinewave (default) Z=1     Use ramp down Z=2     Use squarewave

@ENDNODE

@NODE SetFinetuneValue "Set Finetune Value"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command E5z: SET FINETUNE VALUE:@{ub}
Sets the finetune value for a channel. The finetune can vary from -8
to 7 (using 2's complement, ie 0 to 7 are represented by the numbers
0 to 7, and -8 to -1 are represented by the numbers 8 to F).

| C 101E5E |     <--| Set the finetune value to -2 |

@ENDNODE

@NODE PatternLoop "PatternLoop"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command E6z: PATTERN LOOP:@{ub}
Used for creating loops in patterns. First the first row of the loop
must be defined, by using Z = 0, and then at the end of the loop, the
number of "jump backs" are defined with Z > 0. Nested loops (inside
each other) are not possible.

| C 303E60 |     <--| Beginning of the loop |
| ...      |
|    00E64 |     <--| The loop will be replayed 4 times, then |
                    | continue                                |

@ENDNODE

@NODE SetTremoloWaveform "SetTremoloWaveform"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command E7z: SET TREMOLO WAVEFORM:@{ub}
Like command E4z, but sets waveform for tremolo instead.

@ENDNODE

@NODE RetrigNote "Retrig Note"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command E9z: RETRIG NOTE:@{ub}
Plays the note every Z VBL's (see effect Fyz). Useful is you want to
play the pattern slowly, but want say, a hihat playing rapidly.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FineVolumeSlideUp "Fine Volume Slide, Up"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command EAz: FINE VOLUMESLIDE, UP:@{ub}
Simply adds the argument to the current volume of the channel.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FineVolumeSlideDown "Fine Volume Slide, Down"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command EBz: FINE VOLUMESLIDE, DOWN:@{ub}
Simply subtracts the argument from the current volume.

@ENDNODE

@NODE NoteCut "Note Cut"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command ECz: NOTECUT:@{ub}
Cuts the note after Z VBL's (see effect E9z), ie sets the volume to
00.

@ENDNODE

@NODE NoteDelay "Note Delay"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command EDz: NOTE DELAY:@{ub}
Waits Z VBL's, before playing the note.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PatternDelay "Pattern Delay"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}Command EFz: PATTERN DELAY:@{ub}
Delays the pattern Z VBL's. Useful for creating a short pause in the
music.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Differences "Effects That Differ From the NT-Fornat"
@TOC Main_Music
@{b}EFFECTS THAT DIFFER FROM THE NT-FORMAT:@{ub}
Some effects differ slightly from the nt-format. These are effect
9yz, 4yz (new for 2.03), and effect Byz. These differences are autimagically converted
when a module is loaded/saved in NT-format.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AppA "Appendix A"
@TOC Main
@{b}APPENDIX A  IFF EMOD FILE FORMAT:@{ub}
The standard @{"EMOD" LINK Words} fileformat is using the standard IFF (not 
SMUS!) format. It was necessary to create a new fileformat, to be able 
to include all the new features (compared to the NT-fileformat), like:

     * 255x128 kb samples.

     * 256x256 rows named patterns.

     * 255 positions.

     * Better internal format for pattern data - 4 bits left per note 
	  for future expansion.


The patterndata is put in the file row by row, 4 bytes for each 
note, and 16 bytes for each row:

SampleNr NoteNr   Empty Effect 
                        cmd.
-------- -------- ----  -------------
00000000 00000000 0000  0000-00000000        <--- Bits
-------- -------- ---------- --------  
Byte 0   Byte 1   Byte 2     Byte 3    

The notenumber is a number from 0 to 35 which corresponds to a 
note (C 1 to B 3). To get the period you'll have to use a list. The following 
are  the IFF chunks of the @{"EMOD" LINK Words} fileformat. If you want to add something 
new to the module like a long comment or a text, please make a new 
chunk. A properly made program should just ignore the unknown chunks.


Type      Size Description
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
char	     4    "FORM"
long	     4    Size of file from offset 8

*********** Infochunk ************

char      4    "EMOD"				;Extended Module
char      4    "EMIC"				;Extended Module Info Chunk
long      4    Size of chunk
word      2    Version of IFF EMIC-chunk
char      20   Name of song
char      20   Composer
byte      1    Tempo
byte      1    Number of samples
  byte    1    Sample nr
  byte    1    Volume
  word    2    Samplelength in words
  char    20   Name of sample
  byte    1    Controlbyte bit 0=loop on/off
  byte    1    First 4 bits finetune 
  word    2    Repeat in words		;Length to loop repeatpoint
  word    2    Replen in words		;Length of loop
  long    4    Offset to the sample from the very beginning of the 
               file

byte      1    Pad
byte      1    Nr of patterns
  byte    1    Pattern nr
  byte    1    Length of pattern in rows - 1
  char    20   Name of pattern
  long    4    Offset to the pattern from the beginning of the file

byte      1    Pad
byte      1    Nr of positions
  byte    1    Patternnumber

byte      0 or 1 Extra byte to wordalign if necessary.


******** Pattern data chunk **********

char      4	"PATT"                   ;Patterndata
long      4	Size of chunk
byte	16   row 1
byte 16   row 2
byte 16   row 3...


******** Sample data chunk *********

char	4    "8SMP"              ;8 - bit SaMPle
long	4    Size of chunk
byte	?    Sampledata

@ENDNODE


@NODE AppB "Appendix B"
@TOC Main
@{b}APPENDIX B  HISTORY:@{ub}

Version   Change
----------------------------------------------------------------------
2.0       * Everything
2.01      * Fixed some bugs:
          * The Load Module Menu choise made the computer crash if you
            didn't have Magic Menu installed.
          * The Editskip keyboard shortcut did more than it should.
2.011     * Eine kleine bug in the Synth fixed.
          * Op & Exit Echo does now work.
          * Warns if 'diskfont.library' isn't found.
          (About three lines in the source changed.)
2.02      * Added "Pattern" to samplelist.
2.021     * Fixed OS3.0 screenbar bug.
2.03      * Made the menus look good on 3.0's. Unfortunately, they
            look like hell when using Magic Menu.
          * Noise in the synth addded.
          * The vibrato depth is now halved when loading/saving NT modules.
          * The graphics task doesn't freeze when closing the spect or scope window
            anymore (it used do to so sometimes).
          * The CIA / VBlank timing status is now saved in the pref file.
          * The keyboard buffer is cleared when playing sounds in the sample editor.
          * "Play"-time added.
          * The frequency of the vblank interrupt is now checked. The samplepointers 
            will be in the correct position all the time.
          * The envelopes in the synth are now save- and loadable.
          * Fixed a save NT module bug.
2.031     * Fixed another save NT module bug (flipped out when too many samples).
2.1       * Fixed a lot of bugs.
          * Added center to sample window.
          * Added resample to sample edit window.
          * Added pitch to sample edit window.
          * Added analyze to sample edit window.
          * It is now possible to mark blocks with the keyboard.
          * Added MIDI in.
          * Added split keyboard.
          * Added AmigaGuide online help.
          * Rewrote this manual.
@ENDNODE
